<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" box="[151,227,581,605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,227,581,605]" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" reason="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,227,581,605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Imago</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,617,642]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
1) Head strongly shaded with black between ocelli; head and pronotum color pattern as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1918,1941]" captionTargetBox="[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-262@2.[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 1—Head and pronotum of female; 2—Head and pronotum of male; 3— Abdominal color pattern of female; and 4—Abdominal color pattern of male (scale: figs. 1–2: 1.0mm and figs. 3–4: 5.0mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286146/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
Figs. 1 
<emphasis box="[1422,1436,618,641]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
2; 2
</figureCitation>
) forewing length: male— 
<quantity box="[498,654,653,677]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.27" metricValueMin="1.13" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" unit="mm" value="12.0" valueMax="12.7" valueMin="11.3">
11.3 
<emphasis box="[544,558,654,677]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
12.7mm
</quantity>
; females—15.0 
<emphasis box="[832,846,654,677]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
17.0mm; 3) wings hyaline with veins C, Sc and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1428,1436,668,682]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">1</subScript>
grayish on basal 3/4; 4) parastyli long and straight or only subtly curved (
<figureCitation box="[968,1051,692,716]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1715,1738]" captionTargetBox="[177,1433,203,1684]" captionTargetId="figure-140@3.[151,1436,193,1694]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–11. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 5—Male forewing; 6—Male hind wing; 7—Female forewing; 8—Female hindwing; 9—Detail of penes; 10—Male genitalia (lateral view); 11—Male genitalia (ventral view); 12—Detail of female parastyli receptors; and 13 – Female VIII sternum (scale: figs. 5 and 7: 5.0mm; figs. 6 and 8, 10–11 and 13: 0.1mm; figs. 9 and 12: 0.5mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286150" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286150/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
); 5) penes long, slender and cylindrical, apically hooked (
<figureCitation box="[423,533,728,752]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1715,1738]" captionTargetBox="[177,1433,203,1684]" captionTargetId="figure-140@3.[151,1436,193,1694]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–11. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 5—Male forewing; 6—Male hind wing; 7—Female forewing; 8—Female hindwing; 9—Detail of penes; 10—Male genitalia (lateral view); 11—Male genitalia (ventral view); 12—Detail of female parastyli receptors; and 13 – Female VIII sternum (scale: figs. 5 and 7: 5.0mm; figs. 6 and 8, 10–11 and 13: 0.1mm; figs. 9 and 12: 0.5mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286150" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286150/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 9 
<emphasis box="[490,504,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
11
</figureCitation>
); 6) female parastyli receptors “C” shaped, receptors large, occupying nearly all extension of sternum VIII (Figs. 12 
<emphasis box="[547,561,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
13).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,504,799,825]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[199,344,799,824]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[354,504,800,825]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Male imago:</emphasis>
</emphasis>
Length (mm): 11.0 
<emphasis box="[732,746,801,824]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
13.0 body; 11.3 
<emphasis box="[928,942,801,824]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
12.7 forewing; 5.0 
<emphasis box="[1155,1169,801,824]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
5.2 hind wing. General coloration thorax yellowish and abdomen whitish suffused with gray and black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,257,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[275,344,872,896]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1918,1941]" captionTargetBox="[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-262@2.[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 1—Head and pronotum of female; 2—Head and pronotum of male; 3— Abdominal color pattern of female; and 4—Abdominal color pattern of male (scale: figs. 1–2: 1.0mm and figs. 3–4: 5.0mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286146/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
): Yellowish; anterior margin whitish. Head heavily suffused with black; base of ocelli and area between the ocelli nearly completely black. Ocelli white. Eyes black. Scape and pedicel white shaded with gray; flagellum translucent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,287,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Thorax:</emphasis>
Pronotum yellowish white; anterior hump translucent white. Color pattern as in 
<figureCitation box="[1235,1307,980,1004]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1918,1941]" captionTargetBox="[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-262@2.[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 1—Head and pronotum of female; 2—Head and pronotum of male; 3— Abdominal color pattern of female; and 4—Abdominal color pattern of male (scale: figs. 1–2: 1.0mm and figs. 3–4: 5.0mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286146/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
. Meso and metanotum yellowish suffused with black, particularly among suture lines of mesonotum. Prosternum translucent white. Meso and metasternum yellowish, both with blackish marking on median region; marking longer on mesosternum; mesofurcasternal plates approximating each other on anterior half, with mesofurcasternal impression narrow on that half and wide on posterior half.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,259,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Legs:</emphasis>
Fore leg: coxa, trochanter, femur and tibia yellowish; femur and tibia heavily shaded with gray, with an apical marking on femur. Tarsomeres translucent white heavily suffused with gray, shade becoming more fainted toward apical segments. Tarsal claws white. Mid and hind legs: yellowish, femur and tibia shaded with gray.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,265,1269,1292]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Wings</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[281,430,1268,1292]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1715,1738]" captionTargetBox="[177,1433,203,1684]" captionTargetId="figure-140@3.[151,1436,193,1694]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–11. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 5—Male forewing; 6—Male hind wing; 7—Female forewing; 8—Female hindwing; 9—Detail of penes; 10—Male genitalia (lateral view); 11—Male genitalia (ventral view); 12—Detail of female parastyli receptors; and 13 – Female VIII sternum (scale: figs. 5 and 7: 5.0mm; figs. 6 and 8, 10–11 and 13: 0.1mm; figs. 9 and 12: 0.5mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286150" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286150/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Figs. 5 and 7</figureCitation>
): Membrane hyaline; base of wings gray. Fore wing: veins C, Sc and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1240,1248,1283,1297]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">1</subScript>
gray, whitish on apical third, membrane of wing in this region also whitish. Remaining veins translucent-white. Hind wing: veins C and Sc gray on basal half; vein R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[522,530,1358,1372]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">1</subScript>
gray only at base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,302,1381,1405]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Abdomen</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[322,394,1381,1405]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1918,1941]" captionTargetBox="[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-262@2.[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 1—Head and pronotum of female; 2—Head and pronotum of male; 3— Abdominal color pattern of female; and 4—Abdominal color pattern of male (scale: figs. 1–2: 1.0mm and figs. 3–4: 5.0mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286146/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
): Whitish with longitudinal medial line translucent white; terga I 
<emphasis box="[1166,1180,1382,1405]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
VII shaded with gray, except for median line. Tergum VIII heavily shaded obstructing median line; terga IX 
<emphasis box="[1105,1119,1418,1441]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
X heavily shaded with black or a darker gray, without median line. Sterna translucent white with lateral swellings yellowish; sterna suffused with gray medially; sterna VII 
<emphasis box="[490,504,1490,1513]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
IX heavily suffused. Sterna VIII 
<emphasis box="[864,878,1490,1513]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
IX more heavily suffused. Sternum IX entire with posterior margin and a pair of lateral lines black. Caudal filaments translucent white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,303,1562,1586]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[323,446,1561,1585]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1715,1738]" captionTargetBox="[177,1433,203,1684]" captionTargetId="figure-140@3.[151,1436,193,1694]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–11. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 5—Male forewing; 6—Male hind wing; 7—Female forewing; 8—Female hindwing; 9—Detail of penes; 10—Male genitalia (lateral view); 11—Male genitalia (ventral view); 12—Detail of female parastyli receptors; and 13 – Female VIII sternum (scale: figs. 5 and 7: 5.0mm; figs. 6 and 8, 10–11 and 13: 0.1mm; figs. 9 and 12: 0.5mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286150" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286150/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
Figs. 9 
<emphasis box="[405,419,1562,1585]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
11
</figureCitation>
): Translucent white; parastyli light brown. Parastyli straight or at most only subtly curved; forming an angle of about 45 
<superScript attach="left" box="[567,575,1597,1611]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">o</superScript>
in relation to penes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,371,1636,1661]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Female imago:</emphasis>
Length (mm): 11.5 
<emphasis box="[588,602,1637,1660]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
12.5 body; 15.0 
<emphasis box="[776,790,1637,1660]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
17.0 forewing; 6.0 
<emphasis box="[996,1010,1637,1660]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">–</emphasis>
7.2 hind wing. General coloration yellow suffused with black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,257,1709,1733]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[275,341,1708,1732]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1918,1941]" captionTargetBox="[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-262@2.[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 1—Head and pronotum of female; 2—Head and pronotum of male; 3— Abdominal color pattern of female; and 4—Abdominal color pattern of male (scale: figs. 1–2: 1.0mm and figs. 3–4: 5.0mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286146/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
): Yellowish; anterior margin whitish. Head heavily suffused with black; base of ocelli and area between the ocelli nearly completely black. Ocelli white. Eyes black. Scape and pedicel white shaded with gray; flagellum translucent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,287,1816,1840]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Thorax:</emphasis>
Yellow; Pronotum with anterior ring heavily suffused with black, color pattern as in 
<figureCitation box="[1246,1312,1816,1840]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1918,1941]" captionTargetBox="[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-262@2.[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 1—Head and pronotum of female; 2—Head and pronotum of male; 3— Abdominal color pattern of female; and 4—Abdominal color pattern of male (scale: figs. 1–2: 1.0mm and figs. 3–4: 5.0mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286146/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
. Meso and metanotum heavily shaded with black; particularly among suture lines of mesonotum. Prosternum yellow lightly suffused with black. Meso and metasternum yellow heavily suffused with black on median region, forming blackish markings medially. Mesofurcasternal plates approximating each other on anterior half, with mesofurcasternal impression narrow on that half and wide on posterior half.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,581,2020]" box="[197,1037,1996,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,259,1997,2020]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="51">Legs:</emphasis>
Yellow; with black shade on femur and tibia; foreleg heavily shaded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,652]" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis box="[197,265,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Wings</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[282,432,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1715,1738]" captionTargetBox="[177,1433,203,1684]" captionTargetId="figure-140@3.[151,1436,193,1694]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–11. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 5—Male forewing; 6—Male hind wing; 7—Female forewing; 8—Female hindwing; 9—Detail of penes; 10—Male genitalia (lateral view); 11—Male genitalia (ventral view); 12—Detail of female parastyli receptors; and 13 – Female VIII sternum (scale: figs. 5 and 7: 5.0mm; figs. 6 and 8, 10–11 and 13: 0.1mm; figs. 9 and 12: 0.5mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286150" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286150/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Figs. 6 and 8</figureCitation>
): Membrane hyaline. Forewing: veins S, Sc and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1013,1021,167,181]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">1</subScript>
gray on basal 3/4; whitish on apical fourth; membrane on this region also whitish. Hind wing: vein C and Sc gray on basal half; vein R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1283,1291,206,220]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">1</subScript>
gray only at base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,652]" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis box="[197,302,265,289]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Abdomen</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[319,386,265,289]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1918,1941]" captionTargetBox="[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-262@2.[241,1346,708,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Tortopsis canum sp. nov. Imago. 1—Head and pronotum of female; 2—Head and pronotum of male; 3— Abdominal color pattern of female; and 4—Abdominal color pattern of male (scale: figs. 1–2: 1.0mm and figs. 3–4: 5.0mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286146/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
): Yellow; when without egg, abdomen translucent white. Terga heavily suffused with black. Sterna suffused with black particularly on lateral swellings. Sternum VIII with lateral C-shaped parastyli receptors; outer margin of parastyli receptors shaded black posteriorly. Parastyli receptors large, occupying nearly all the extension of the sternum VIII. Eggs light yellow, bowl-shaped; without polar caps or any attachment structures. Caudal filaments translucent white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,652]" box="[199,417,445,470]" pageId="2" pageNumber="52">
